      "side": 1,
      "message": "In the GWT UI we made a conscious decision for plugins to block UI loading, and for the UI to error if a plugin fails to load. The reason was a site may install a plugin that is critical to the site functioning correctly, and if it fails to load, the site should break with an error rather than leave a user thinking its working as intended.\n\nChromium\u0027s chumpdetector is a good example of a plugin that should be loaded and working before it is possible for a user to reach for that incredibly tempting \"Submit\" button.\n\nOther plugins may just need to be loaded up front to minimize UI layouts and repaints later on when they begin to also add themselves to the DOM.\n\nI can understand why we might revisit this decision, but know that it was discussed before in the context of the plugins in the GWT UI and for reasons (maybe lost to time? I hope its in repo-discuss archives and/or on relevant code reviews in Gerrit!) we went with blocking loading, even though it slowed down initial page view.",
